"ogimage":"http://s3-media2.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/xfXfoi4PCz-3ifLTaYNGcw/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"(Let&#39;s put aside the fact that I&#39;m vegan. There are times I will socially eat meat. Don&#39;t hate.) <br><br>GETTING THERE: The restaurant is located in The Central Mall on the 2nd floor. Near the escalators. This mall is like a labyrinth so try not to get lost. <br><br>DEJA VU: When I saw &#34;8 Korean BBQ&#34; I immediately thought of Palsaik, a Korean bbq joint back in Ktown LA. The menu looked especially familiar. The flavors were the exact same as Palsaik&#39;s. Turns out the two restaurants are under the same owner. <br><br>TASTE: I used to be a hardcore carnivore. Meat and carbs all day. So I know a tasty piece of meat when I encounter one. 8 Korean BBQ is legit yo. I didn&#39;t expect much because if you&#39;ve dined at Koreatown LA many times before, you know what&#39;s hot and not. 8 Korean BBQ is hot. <br><br>Their pork belly is JUICY. Their kimchi is a bit salty though. At least the day I had it. So awesome they had brown rice instead of white rice. Puts a smile on a health nut&#39;s face. <br><br>INSTRUCTIONS: Take a piece of lettuce, place on a pink round radish, a slice of pork, then some kimchi. Wrap it up and into your mouth. Repeat. <br><br>PRICING: 8 Korean BBQ is pricier than Palsaik. The set of eight flavors at Palsaik costs $50. The similar set, if not exactly the same, is double in Singapore&#39;s sister location. But if love K-bbq, it&#39;s worth every penny. Their juicy pork belly will not fail to disappoint. <br><br>CONCLUSION: If you ever miss Koreatown LA, you know where to go... 8 Korean BBQ. Make sure you order a bottle of soju with your meal. Gunbae! Cheers! And if you get drunk, don&#39;t fall into the river. Those stairs are steep. Please have a designated walking buddy.",
